 developed medieval Roman law into a system of rules that formed a universal common law for Western Europe. Because there has been little research published in English beyond grand narratives on the history of law in Europe, this book fills an important gap in the literature.With a focus on how the medieval Roman lawyers systematised the Roman sources through detailed discussions of specific areas of law, it considers:The sources of medieval law and how to access themThe development from cases to rulesMedieval lawyers’ strategies for citing each other and their significanceThe growth of a conceptual approach to the study of lawWith contributions from leading international scholars in the field, this book fills an important gap in the literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aLaw. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aBezemer, Kees, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrundage, James A, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCairns, John W, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDondorp, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErnst, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordley, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHallebeek, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelmholz, Richard H, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlessis, Paul J du, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRyan, Magnus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRüfner, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchrage, Eltjo J H, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWael